\begin_layout Title
Oet for single traces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic relations of the Dirac operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In twisted basis the Dirac operators obeys the relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{u}-M_{d}=2\mu i\gamma_{5}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying from the left by the inverse of the Dirac operator of the up
 quark, and from the right by the down one, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{d}^{-1}-M_{u}^{-1}=2\mu iM_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}M_{d}^{-1},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now rotating to physical basis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{i\pi\gamma_{5}/4}S_{d}^{-1}e^{i\pi\gamma_{5}/4}-e^{-i\pi\gamma_{5}/4}S_{u}^{-1}e^{-i\pi\gamma_{5}/4}=2\mu ie^{-i\pi\gamma_{5}/4}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}e^{i\pi\gamma_{5}/4},
\]

\end_inset

which means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{d}^{-1}e^{i\pi\gamma_{5}/2}-e^{-i\pi\gamma_{5}/2}S_{u}^{-1}=2\mu ie^{-i\pi\gamma_{5}/2}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}e^{i\pi\gamma_{5}/2},
\]

\end_inset

remembering that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\pm i\pi\gamma_{5}/2}=\pm i\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{d}^{-1}\gamma_{5}+\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}=2\mu\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\gamma_{5},
\]

\end_inset

multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

 from the right one gets:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{d}^{-1}+\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}=2\mu\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Application to the single trace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the trace with a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\pm\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\right]=2\mu{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

(-) must be taken if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 commutes (anticommutes) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

, which means:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccccccccccccccc}
S & V_{x} & V_{y} & V_{z} & V_{t} & P & A_{x} & A_{y} & A_{z} & A_{t} & T_{1} & T_{2} & T_{3} & B_{1} & B_{2} & B_{3}\\
+ & - & - & - & - & + & - & - & - & - & + & + & + & + & + & +
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So if we are interested in computing the sum, which is the physically-meaningful
 quantity, we can apply the method only to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S,\,P,\,T,\,B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What does it mean?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remembering that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pm{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\right]={\rm Tr}\left[\gamma_{5}\Gamma\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\right]={\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\gamma_{5}\right]={\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma\left(S_{d}^{-1}\right)^{\dagger}\right]=\pm^{\prime}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma^{\dagger}\left(S_{d}^{-1}\right)^{\dagger}\right]=\pm^{\prime}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\right]^{\ast}
\]

\end_inset

one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\pm\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\right]={\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\right]\pm^{\prime}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\right]^{\ast}=2{\rm Re}/{\rm Im}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{d}^{-1}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where the imaginary part holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is antihermitean, as per the following table:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccccccccccccccc}
S & V_{x} & V_{y} & V_{z} & V_{t} & P & A_{x} & A_{y} & A_{z} & A_{t} & T_{1} & T_{2} & T_{3} & B_{1} & B_{2} & B_{3}\\
Re & Re & Re & Re & Re & Re & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, the OET is actually 
\bar under
a trick to compute the real part, or the imaginary
\bar default
, but not both.
 This relation holds no matter the regularization! It is true also in Wilson
 regularization, where it simply reads:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\rm Re}/{\rm Im}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S^{-1}\right]=\mu{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma\gamma_{5}S^{-1}\gamma_{5}S^{-1}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Physically, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{r}^{-1}\left(x,x\right)\right]^{\ast}={\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma^{\dagger}S_{r}^{-1}\left(x,x\right)^{\dagger}\right]=\pm\pm^{\prime}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{-r}^{-1}\left(x,x\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now since the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is immaterial in the physical world, the trace is real or imaginary depending
 on its commutation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

 and hermiticity, according to the following relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccccccccccccccc}
S & V_{x} & V_{y} & V_{z} & V_{t} & P & A_{x} & A_{y} & A_{z} & A_{t} & T_{1} & T_{2} & T_{3} & B_{1} & B_{2} & B_{3}\\
Re & Im & Im & Im & Im & Re & Re & Re & Re & Re & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im & Im
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining this with the previous table, one reads immediately that the method
 allows one to compute only the physical part of the following bubbles:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S,\,P,\,T,\,B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Why is this supposedly better?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ok we have understood that writing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\equiv\mu{\rm Tr}\sum_{\vec{x},y}\left[\Gamma\gamma_{5}S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\left(y;\vec{x},t\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\equiv{\rm Tr}\sum_{\vec{x}}\left[\Gamma S_{d/u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;\vec{x},t\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\in\left\{ S,\,P,\,T,\,B\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Since this is an analytical property, it is hard to understand why this
 should be better.
 It is actually possible to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 in two different ways.
 One can either create a volume source 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 or a wall source 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}\left(x\right)=\eta\left(x\right)\delta_{x_{0},t}$
\end_inset

.
 For the time being we focus on the volume source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One defines the stochastic propagator: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(x\right)=S_{u}^{-1}\left(x;y\right)\eta\left(y\right),
\]

\end_inset

then one get the estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\equiv\sum_{\vec{x}}\eta^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\Gamma\phi\left(\vec{x},t\right),
\]

\end_inset

in facts it is easy to see that the expectation value is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =\sum_{\vec{x},y}\left\langle \eta^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(x;y\right)\eta\left(y\right)\right\rangle =\sum_{\vec{x}}{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;\vec{x},t\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When it comes to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 one can use the following estimator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\equiv\mu\sum_{\vec{x}}\left[\phi^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\Gamma\phi\left(\vec{x},t\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

which has the correct expectation value since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & =\mu\sum_{\vec{x},y,z}\left[\eta^{\dagger}\left(z\right)S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;z\right)^{\dagger}\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\eta\left(y\right)\right]=,\\
 & =\mu{\rm Tr}\sum_{\vec{x},y}\left[\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\left(y;\vec{x},t\right)\gamma_{5}\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is what needed.
 Since in both cases we have used 1 stochastic propagator, it is not clear
 what is the advantage.
 To understand it, we should estimate the variance.
 We should notice that introducing the stochastic source is equivalent to
 reintroduce the quark fields (with bosonic statistics).
 Let us start from the disconnected version:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)=\left\langle \left|d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\right\rangle -\left|\left\langle d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \right|^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \left|d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)d_{\Gamma}^{\ast}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =\sum_{\vec{x},\vec{y}}\left\langle {\rm Tr}\left[\eta^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\Gamma\phi\left(\vec{x},t\right)\right]{\rm Tr}\left[\phi^{\dagger}\left(\vec{y},t\right)\Gamma^{\dagger}\eta\left(\vec{y},t\right)\right]\right\rangle =
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{\vec{x},\vec{y},z,w}\left\langle \eta^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;z\right)\eta\left(z\right)\eta^{\dagger}\left(w\right)S_{u}^{-1\dagger}\left(\vec{y},tw;\right)\Gamma^{\dagger}\eta\left(\vec{y},t\right)\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \prod_{i=1}^{N}\eta\left(x_{i}\right)\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, as is the case of gaussian noise, the only contractions are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \left|d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\right\rangle  & =\left|{\rm Tr}\left[\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;\vec{x},t\right)\right]\right|^{2}+\\
 & +{\rm Tr}\sum_{y}\left[S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\left(y;\vec{x},t\right)\gamma_{5}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first line is the same of the modulus square of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, whereas using 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

 hermiticity one can rewrite the second as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}d_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)={\rm Tr}\left[\sum_{y}\left|S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\right|^{2}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coming to the second estimator, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)=\left\langle \left|c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\right\rangle -\left|\left\langle c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \right|^{2}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \left|c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)c_{\Gamma}^{\ast}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\mu^{2}\sum_{\vec{x},y,z}\left[\eta^{\dagger}\left(z\right)S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;z\right)^{\dagger}\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\eta\left(y\right)\right]\sum_{\vec{x}^{\prime},y^{\prime},z^{\prime}}\left[\eta^{\dagger}\left(y^{\prime}\right)S_{u}^{-1\dagger}\left(\vec{x}^{\prime},t;y^{\prime}\right)\Gamma^{\dagger}S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x}^{\prime},t;z^{\prime}\right)\eta\left(z^{\prime}\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dropping from the beginning the disconnected contraction, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}c_{\Gamma}\left(t\right)=\mu^{2}{\rm Tr}\sum_{y,z}\left|\sum_{\vec{x}}\gamma_{5}S_{d}^{-1}\left(z;\vec{x},t\right)\gamma_{5}\Gamma S_{u}^{-1}\left(\vec{x},t;y\right)\right|^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this better? If yes, why?
\end_layout

